    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "This is fundamentally a proposed enhancement.\n\nThe Vim `compiler/:make` system is a real boon to productivity that I've only recently started to really explore. \n\nOne of its shortcomings are the limitations of the 'errorformat' system. The docs hint at them with the suggestion of adding a filter to the 'makeprg' setting to product \"formattable\" output. The problem there is that the filter conceals the error code of the make program, which can be useful for other tools.\n\nWhat I'm proposing is an 'errorfunc' setting, that would consume the output of 'makeprg' as a list of lines and be directly responsible for populating the appropriate quickfix/location list. The default implementation would examine the 'errorformat' setting and behave exactly as the current system does.\n",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "I believe nobody likes writing `'errorformat'`. I'd rather leverage `vim.re`, `vim.regex` or `vim.lpeg` ([My plugin](https://github.com/msaher/bufix.nvim) uses `vim.lpeg` to parse errors so I can escape setting `'errorformat'`)\n\nI think an `'errorfunc'` can solve this well. A few thoughts:\n\n- `'errorformat'`'s `%D` keeps track of directories in a stack\n- `'errorformat'` supports multiline error messages\n- `'errorformat'` is a *list* of formats, not just one.\n\nWhat should the signature of an `'errorfunc'` be?\n\nInitial suggestion: It takes `line: string` and returns `nil` on failure. On success it returns a table of the type:\n\n```lua\n{\n    filename: string,\n    line?: number,\n    line_end?: number,\n    col?: number,\n    col_end?: number,\n    type?: \"error\" | \"warning\" | \"info\" | \"note\",\n}\n```\n\nWhat about multiline error messages? We can either not support them (I don't know of any tool that doesn't show everything in one line) or we can let error functions *signal* that they're not done parsing by an aditional value, say `\"continue\"`. The function can maintain state elsewhere. Example:\n\n```lua\n-- Imagine a simple multi-line error message that looks like this\n-- FILE: myfile\n-- LINE: 5\nlocal state = { expecting = \"file\" }\nlocal res = {}\nfunction myerrorfunc(line)\n    if state.expecting == \"file\" then\n        if vim.startswith(line, \"FILE:\") then\n            res = {}\n            res.filename = \"\" -- blah blah\n            state.expecting = \"line\"\n            return res, \"continue\" -- we are not done yet\n        else\n            return nil -- give up\n        end\n    elseif state.expecting == \"line\" then\n        if vim.startswith(line, \"LINE:\") then\n            res.line = \"\" -- blah blah\n            return res -- we are done. Complete result\n        else\n            return res -- no line number found. return partial results\n        end\n    else\n        return nil\n    end\nend\n```\n\nLetting functions track state is also how we can track directory stacks.\n\nWhat about state resets on clean runs? Maybe an optional second argument `errorfunc(line, true)` that signals that we are running in a new state? Still have to think more about that one.\n\nIt's worth mentioning that the overwhelming majority of error functions only care about parsing a single line. Hence, the design should optimize for the common use case.\n\nRelated side note: I dislike how I'm expected to manually pick compilers to get the right `'errorformat'`. I prefer the way Emacs' `M-x compile` keeps track of a long list of regular expressions to try such that parsing errors \"just works\". I'd dislike plugins from overwriting `'errorfunc'`, but to rather encourage them to wrap the current `'errorfunc'` instead. Or do we make `errorfunc'` list of functions to mirror `'errorformat'`?\n",
            "created_at": "2026-06-16T13:43:56Z",
